label("3",(1,8.95)--(5,10),NW);
label("10",(0,0)--(0,10),W);
[/asy]

solution:
Step 1: To calculate the total surface area of the cylinder, we cut off the two ends to obtain two circles of radius 3.
Step 2: [asy]
Step 3: draw(circle((3,3),3),black+linewidth(1));
Step 4: draw((3,3)--(5.1213,3-2.1213),black+linewidth(1));
Step 5: draw(circle((11,3),3),black+linewidth(1));
Step 6: draw((11,3)--(13.1213,3-2.1213),black+linewidth(1));
Step 7: label("3",(3,3)--(5.1213,3-2.1213),SW);
Step 8: label("3",(11,3)--(13.1213,3-2.1213),SW);
Step 9: [/asy]
Step 10: The two ends combined have an area of 2pi r^2 = 2 pi(3^2)=18pi. Next, we must calculate the lateral surface area. To do this, we make a vertical cut through this area, and unroll the lateral surface. When we do this, we obtain a rectangle with height 10. The width of the rectangle (ie. the length of the top edge) is equal to the circumference of one of the ends, since the top edge of this rectangle lay exactly along the circumference of the top end.
Step 11: [asy]
Step 12: draw((0,0)--(15,0)--(15,10)--(0,10)--cycle,black+linewidth(1));
Step 13: label("10",(0,0)--(0,10),W);
Step 14: [/asy]
Step 15: The circumference of one of the ends is 2pi r = 2pi(3)=6pi, so the width of the rectangle is 6pi. Therefore, the area of this rectangle is 10* 6pi = 60pi. So the total surface area of the cylinder is 18pi + 60pi = 78pi.
Answer: 78pi

