Step 8: draw((-2,0)--(0,0));
Step 9: label("A",(-2,0),W); label("O",(0,0),E); label("B",(2,0),E);
Step 10: [/asy]
Step 11: Since the smaller circle and the larger circle touch at A, the diameter through A of the smaller circle lies along the diameter through A of the larger circle. (This is because each diameter is perpendicular to the common tangent at the point of contact.)
Step 12: Since AO is a radius of the larger circle, it is a diameter of the smaller circle.
Step 13: Since the radius of the larger circle is 6, the diameter of the smaller circle is 6, so the radius of the smaller circle on the left is 3.
Step 14: Similarly, we can draw a radius through O and B and deduce that the radius of the smaller circle on the right is also 3. The area of the shaded region equals the area of the larger circle minus the combined area of the two smaller circles. Thus, the area of the shaded region is 6^2pi - 3^2pi - 3^2pi = 36pi - 9pi - 9pi = 18pi.
Answer: 18pi

